issue.title: variant: how to inherit some of the parent fields
issue.body:
I am looking to setup a model for wine, and I'm wondering how to efficiently set up the variants.
There is a new variant every year having the same
- name
- wine type (red, rosé, white, ..)
but different
- grape varieties (cépage in French)
- price
- vintage

This is not an urgent oscar issue but I hope it's still is a valid question because of the parent inheritance.

**Technical details**

- Python version: 3.10.12
- Django version: 4.2.6
- Oscar version: 3.2.2

comment.body:
A little harsh but I get it :-)
I did ask in the Google group but got no replies.

**Technical details**

- Django version: 4.2.6
- Oscar version: 3.2.2

comment.body:
You can add the “grape variety” attribute and fill it out on every child, if it’s filled it on the child it doesn’t look at it’s parents attribute value.

This way you can “override” the parents attributes

comment.body:
Hi Christian,

The children inherit the attribute values from the parent.

If you fill these out in parent products and leave them empty in the child products they should appear on the detail page / in the filters.

issue.title: server error with django-phonenumber-field 4.0.0
issue.body:
### Issue Summary
Server error with `ImportError: cannot import name 'force_text' from 'django.utils.encoding'` and Django 4.2.6
In Django 4 `force_text `has been replaced by `force_str`

File "/opt/django/env/lib/python3.10/site-packages/phonenumber_field/modelfields.py", line 4, in <module>
from django.utils.encoding import force_text
ImportError: cannot import name 'force_text' from 'django.utils.encoding' (/opt/django/env/lib/python3.10/site-packages/django/utils/encoding.py)

### Steps to Reproduce

Install 
django-oscar 3.2.2 requires django-phonenumber-field<7.0.0,>=4.0.0, but you have django-phonenumber-field 7.2.0 which is incompatible

1. (for example) Form the catalogue app with `./manage.py oscar_fork_app catalogue myproject/`
2. Edit models.py as follows...
3. ...

Any other relevant information. For example, why do you consider this a bug and what did you expect to happen instead?

### Technical details

* Python version: Run `python --version`.
* Django version: Look in your requirements.txt, or run `pip show django | grep Version`.
* Oscar version: Look in your requirements.txt, or run `pip show django-oscar | grep Version`.
